I wrote GRE in 2015 and scored 330/340 after preparing for 20 days.
I scored 170/170 in Quant and 160/170 in Verbal. I learned words using Barron's 1100 words android application and Word power made easy(Norman Lewis).

Barron's 1100 app link: Barron's 1100 - Android Apps on Google Play
Word power made easy: Buy the book, it's very cheap.

I learned words from only these two sources and almost all the words on actual exam were covered by these two sources. Make sure that you do not simply cram the meanings. Try to understand the context.

I think learning these two sources in their entirety is sufficient for building a decent vocabulary for GRE

Practising Reading Comprehension questions helps a lot. The most important part is to review the solutions of the passages after you have attempted them and understand why all the other answers are wrong. There are 4/5 different variants of trap answers which are common to most passages. I found this link very useful - GMAT RC: Eliminating Wrong Answers. Even though its written for the GMAT, it works in the GRE too.

Best is subjective to the criteria you’re using to evaluate books/courses.

Magoosh - Best Overall Value. With 6 months of access to over 200 video lessons, 1000+ practice questions, and 3 practice tests for $149- this is easily the best value of any course. Plus, they offer a +5 total score guarantee if you’re retaking it. While they don’t offer feedback for AWA essays and don’t have as many practice questions/tests as some of the competition, it’s more than enough for most students.

It is a standardized test that is generally required by universities in the US and certain other universities across the globe. What is a standardized test, you ask? A standardized test is any test which requires all test-takers to a) answer the same questions or questions from a common bank of questions in the same manner and b) that is scored or evaluated in the same manner. This ensures that all test-takers, objectively, have an equal shot at success and also allows for the comparison of the relative performance of an individual.

Now let’s cover the rest of the basics. The GRE exam can be divided broadly into two categories:

The Quantitative Reasoning Section
The Verbal Reasoning Section - Both assessed on a scale of 130-170

Manhattan Strategy Guides: I suggest you start with these. Sentence correction, critical reasoning, reading comprehension, and integrated reasoning & essay. These books will build your basic knowledge and at the same time offer you decent number of questions to practice.

As we Indians are generally good at maths, I would suggest that you start your preparation with the GMAT Quant topics.

It will help you to get in the habit of studying while boosting your confidence at the same time.
After you manage to get a decent accuracy level (say 80%) in the quant section move over to GMAT verbal topics.

Now verbal, as far as I can tell from my experience and from that of my friends’, requires comparatively a lot more effort as we are generally not subjected to this tricky a test of our command over the English language.

The Graduate Management Aptitude Test is a standardized Computer Adaptive Exam taken for admissions into graduate management programs around the globe and majorly in United States. It tests your quantitative, verbal, analytical and writing skills. Several prospective students from various backgrounds aim to get admission in top business schools around the world. GMAT Test offers a good method of choosing the best applicants among several students based on the scores, making the system of selection for management course more transparent.

National Eligibility cum EntranceTest 

It's a entrance examination in India, for students who wish to study any graduate medical course (MBBS ), dental course ( BDS) or postgraduate course (MD / MS ) in government or private medical colleges in India.

Clearing the NEET needs hard work, dedication and strategy.Remember that text books alone won't help, minimise textbooks and maximise MCQ practice.The more you solve ,the more you learn .Also, focus correctly on NCERT .Give timed tests.Then NEET is not tough enough .

And for reference books, surf the ones you feel comfortable with; suggestions will not be that much effective. You will know about standard books on bookstores or from concerned teachers.

If you have any other query regarding NEET , feel free to drop a message .

NCERT Books:

A major portion of NEET Syllabus is covered in the CBSE 11th and 12th board syllabus. Therefore, every student should complete the NCERT books first to understand and clear various concepts. Still, there are certain topics and concepts which the NCERT books do not cover. Hence, in order to gain command over those topics, candidates will need some reference books for NEET.

Check for the complete syllabus and pattern.
Solve last year question papers. This is the best way to prepare for the NEET exam as this will give you a clear idea about the pattern and difficulty level of the questions.
Choose best study materials for your preparation.
Make notes of all the important topics or anything that is important for the exam. This will help you in your last minute preparation.
Take online test series. This will help you analyze your level of preparation and also increase your speed and accuracy.
Improve your weaker areas first. Study more for the topics in which you are weak.
Take Proper sleep.

IIT JEE is one of the toughest engineering entrance exams in India. It is conducted in two tiers- IIT JEE Main and IIT JEE Advanced. Only those candidates appear for IIT JEE Advanced who qualify JEE Main Examination.

IIT JEE Exam is the gateway for IITs, NITs and various other prestigious engineering colleges. Every engineering aspirant wishes to get into IITs and NITs. But cracking IIT JEE Exam is not an easy task. It requires a lot of sincere hard work and perseverance.

It is not practically possible to get an answer from FeQta and some magic tip could make you score 360 in JEE Mains. It does not happen this way.

The people who score well or have scored well at some point in their life (maybe in school), Knows it. You need conceptual understanding and clarity of syllabus to even attempt maximum questions. Even then, there are chances of loosing some marks because you have to do it in a confined time frame.

REVISE - PRACTICE - LEARN - REPEAT is the Key of scoring well in any competitive examination

The exam was in itself much more a game of strategy more than solving in a routine manner . The paper 2 physics was not tough for someone who had spent a lot of time understanding the way things work . The paper tested the application ability of students and it also proved a tough one for students who had worked hard without developing intuition during the JEE Preparation Days .

Coaching for IIT JEE, that too sitting at home can become a bit tedious if done on your own. And if there’s no good tech to support your learning, it becomes a lot more difficult to get hold of concepts. Being someone who was in those shoes long-time back, I can vouch for the experience.

While there are many portals trying to serve the objective, I find Masterclass Space, a specialized software-based online teaching portal which allows interactive and convenient online classes for IIT-JEE students to be a pretty good option. My cousin has enrolled for the course and is loving it to the hilt.

TOEFL- is one of the most challenging tests you will ever take in your life. You need to study hard equally smart to get a highj score on the TOEFL. Here is a list of ten things that will help you get the highest score possible.The TOEFL is the Test of English as a Foreign Language. It is an English proficiency test produced by an American company called ETS. It measures your English reading, listening, speaking, and writing skills, and your ability to succeed at an English-speaking university.

Study material is not the only way to crack TOEFL. It is a test for English to get admissions in foreign Universities. If you regularly read newspapers or if you love reading books and have a good vocab you could easily crack TOEFL.Else you should study from: Barron's Material, Sommersat E-books and Vailor's Book to crack TOEFL.

Actually, it depends on person to person. Starting with the IELTS preparation, give an hour to each module. Practice each and every module in the given time frame. Look out for your mistakes and try not to repeat them, even if you have to listen to that recording once more or you have to read that passage again. Just try not to repeat them. Always try to do the test in the given time limit. Once 60 minutes are over, stop your Reading section and check your answers. After scoring yourself, then solve the remaining questions. Hope you get my point. Same goes with the Listening section.

Set out time everyday to practice your listening skills. Not by listening to music or watching movies! Though that seems like a great solution, with such little time to prepare, it will not serve your purpose. Instead, listen to BBC radio and when you are done, write down a summary, or, explain what you have listened to, to someone.

There is no easy way to say this, but Practice, Practice, Practice! Not just that, say you have practiced. One hour everyday. But you don’t have someone qualified to check your work, so, how do you know if you have written a good essay?

The best way to do this, is to hire a private tutor so you can practice at least one essay everyday. Since you have a month, this would be a minimum of 30 essays before you give your test!

If you are comfortable with speaking, you will breeze through this section. If you aren’t, you should practice speaking with family and friends, to begin with. The best and most constructive way to increase your band score in such a short period wold be to hire a tutor who will have daily, constructive conversations with you to ensure you are ready to tackle any topic.

To summarize, the listening and reading section can be tackled well by you for sure, but do enlist help for the speaking and writing sections.

The help can be in the form of a classroom, study group or a private tutor who is qualified.

You could also opt for online tutors, who would hold class for you at your convenience. Companies like uFaber provide such services.

I hope you crack your test in the time you have! Best of luck!

Reading extensively (be it any news paper, magazines, journals, novels) will give that extra edge to get over the reading and comprehension section in CAT examination. Repeated Maths practice will make you a pro, and you will pass with flying colours in the CATS maths section. There are never long equations in CAT, the only thing which works is the smart way of calculations which can be mastered by practicing the tricks available in books and internet.

The Common Admission Test (CAT) is a 3 hours computer based test held in India. The test scores a candidate on the bases of Quantitative Ability (QA),Verbal Ability (VA) and Reading Comprehension (RC),
Data Interpretation (DI) and Logical Reasoning (LR).
The Indian Institute of Management (IIMs) started this exam and use the test for selecting students for their business administration programs. The test is conducted every year by one of the IIMs based on a policy of rotation.

Try to work on your encyclopedic knowledge, read a lot. This will help you with the verbal section and lead to your overall development. Many times, the language isn’t a barrier in comprehensive exercises, it is the domain knowledge on which the article is based, hence, having a general insight on various topics can always come handy. Focus on topics like economics, sociology, and psychology. No matter how much grammar you mug up, you won’t remember until they register into your subconscious mind via regular usage, when you read frequently, you learn to tell the right usage from the wrong one.

Public Administration is clearly a very good option in which your efforts will be consistent with the syllabus even if the pattern changes. It covers topics of GS and Essay such as polity, budget, good governance etc. It will also be mighty helpful for you in your discharge of duties in case you do qualify. It is easy to study, has a relatively smaller syllabus as compared to Geography and History and it is very easy to find resources for this optional. One thing I will point out here is that recently UPSC has started to ask some unconventional questions in Pub Ad which somebody with only 2-3 months of study can find difficult. These questions require a bit of background knowledge and thorough understanding of concepts. But all in all having Pub Ad as one of the optionals keeping in mind forthcoming changes does make a lot of sense.

Online coaching is getting very popular nowadays. The apparent reason is that UPSC aspirant from diverse section (i.e. college goers, working professionals, house wife etc.) get opportunity to access best IAS online coaching located in Delhi or elsewhere. They can prepare for the exam with their comfort i.e. high flexibility in nature of scheduling their study. They can study early in the morning or late night, even during gap periods of college or office – in other words, higher degree of adjustability is available in online IAS preparation.

The Union Public Service Commission (UPSC) is the central recruiting agency in India. It is an independent constitutional body in the sense that it is directly created by the constitution of India.

The constitution contains elaborate provisions regarding the composition, appointment and removal of members, powers and functions and independence of the UPSC.
